10 min read
Just now

--

Next.js has cemented its place as the go-to React framework for production apps in 2026. But the framework itself is only half the story. The libraries you pair with it determine how fast you ship, how well your app scales, and how much fun you have building it.
This guide covers the libraries the community has actually settled on — not a laundry list of every option that exists, but the ones that show up in real codebases, dominate npm download charts, and get recommended in every serious tech stack discussion today.
1. UI Components
shadcn/ui — The New Default
If you’ve started a new Next.js project this year, shadcn/ui is almost certainly in it. It’s not a traditional component library — there’s no package to install and no version to upgrade. Instead, it copies components directly into your codebase, giving you full ownership and zero dependency lock-in.
Built on top of Radix UI primitives and styled with Tailwind CSS, it strikes the perfect balance between polished defaults and complete customizability.
npx shadcn@latest init
npx shadcn@latest add buttonimport { Button } from "@/components/ui/button"export default function Page() {
return <Button variant="outline">Click me</Button>
}Why it dominates: You own the code, it’s accessible by default, and every component is TypeScript-native. The ecosystem around it — v0, Magic UI, Aceternity UI — has exploded.

Tailwind CSS v4
Tailwind v4 dropped the tailwind.config.js entirely. It's now configured directly in CSS, installs as a Vite plugin, and is significantly faster. If you're on v3, the migration is worth it.
npm install tailwindcss @tailwindcss/vite/* app/globals.css */
@import "tailwindcss";That’s it. No config file, no PostCSS setup. Tailwind just works.

Material UI v7
For enterprise dashboards and SaaS platforms that need a complete design system, MUI v7 remains the go-to. The jump from v5 to v7 delivered roughly a 25% reduction in bundle size by replacing the runtime CSS-in-JS engine with Pigment CSS — a zero-runtime alternative.
npm install @mui/material @emotion/react @emotion/styledimport { Button, TextField } from "@mui/material"export default function LoginForm() {
return (
<form>
<TextField label="Email" variant="outlined" fullWidth />
<Button variant="contained" type="submit">Sign in</Button>
</form>
)
}
Framer Motion
The animation layer for Next.js. Framer Motion’s declarative API makes complex animations manageable — from simple hover effects to orchestrated page transitions and scroll-driven sequences.
npm install framer-motionimport { motion } from "framer-motion"export default function Card() {
return (
<motion.div
initial={{ opacity: 0, y: 20 }}
animate={{ opacity: 1, y: 0 }}
transition={{ duration: 0.4 }}
whileHover={{ scale: 1.02 }}
>
<p>Animated card</p>
</motion.div>
)
}
2. State Management
Zustand — Client State Done Right
Redux is no longer the default for most teams. Zustand has taken over for client-side state management, and for good reason. The API is minimal, there’s no provider boilerplate, and the TypeScript experience is excellent.
npm install zustandimport { create } from "zustand"interface CartStore {
items: string[]
addItem: (item: string) => void
clearCart: () => void
}const useCartStore = create<CartStore>((set) => ({
items: [],
addItem: (item) => set((state) => ({ items: [...state.items, item] })),
clearCart: () => set({ items: [] }),
}))// In any component — no provider needed
export function CartButton() {
const { items, addItem } = useCartStore()
return (
<button onClick={() => addItem("product-1")}>
Cart ({items.length})
</button>
)
}
TanStack Query v5 — Server State Management
TanStack Query (formerly React Query) handles everything related to server state: fetching, caching, background synchronization, and pagination. It works beautifully alongside Zustand — use Zustand for client UI state, TanStack Query for anything that comes from a server.
npm install @tanstack/react-query"use client"
import { useQuery } from "@tanstack/react-query"async function fetchUser(id: string) {
const res = await fetch(`/api/users/${id}`)
return res.json()
}export function UserProfile({ userId }: { userId: string }) {
const { data, isLoading, isError } = useQuery({
queryKey: ["user", userId],
queryFn: () => fetchUser(userId),
staleTime: 5 * 60 * 1000, // 5 minutes
}) if (isLoading) return <p>Loading...</p>
if (isError) return <p>Something went wrong.</p> return <h1>{data.name}</h1>
}
Jotai — Atomic State
When you want something lighter than Zustand or need fine-grained reactivity, Jotai’s atomic model is the answer. State is composed from atoms — tiny pieces that components subscribe to individually.
npm install jotaiimport { atom, useAtom } from "jotai"const themeAtom = atom<"light" | "dark">("light")export function ThemeToggle() {
const [theme, setTheme] = useAtom(themeAtom)
return (
<button onClick={() => setTheme(theme === "light" ? "dark" : "light")}>
{theme === "light" ? "🌙 Dark" : "☀️ Light"}
</button>
)
}
3. Forms & Validation
React Hook Form + Zod — The Unbeatable Combo
These two libraries are almost always used together. React Hook Form handles the form state with minimal re-renders, and Zod handles schema validation with full TypeScript inference.
npm install react-hook-form zod @hookform/resolvers"use client"
import { useForm } from "react-hook-form"
import { zodResolver } from "@hookform/resolvers/zod"
import { z } from "zod"const schema = z.object({
email: z.string().email("Invalid email address"),
password: z.string().min(8, "Password must be at least 8 characters"),
})type FormData = z.infer<typeof schema>export function SignupForm() {
const {
register,
handleSubmit,
formState: { errors, isSubmitting },
} = useForm<FormData>({ resolver: zodResolver(schema) }) const onSubmit = async (data: FormData) => {
await fetch("/api/auth/signup", {
method: "POST",
body: JSON.stringify(data),
})
} return (
<form onSubmit={handleSubmit(onSubmit)}>
<input {...register("email")} placeholder="Email" />
{errors.email && <p>{errors.email.message}</p>} <input type="password" {...register("password")} placeholder="Password" />
{errors.password && <p>{errors.password.message}</p>} <button type="submit" disabled={isSubmitting}>
{isSubmitting ? "Signing up..." : "Sign up"}
</button>
</form>
)
}Note: Zod isn’t just for forms in 2026. It’s used to validate API responses, parse environment variables (via t3-env), and define tRPC input schemas. It's become a foundational utility across the entire stack.

4. Authentication
Better Auth — The 2026 Default for New Projects
Better Auth emerged as the strongest self-hosted authentication solution for TypeScript stacks. You get full data ownership, database sessions with immediate revocation, a rich plugin ecosystem (2FA, passkeys, organization roles), and a code-first setup that fits naturally into modern Next.js apps.
npm install better-auth// lib/auth.ts
import { betterAuth } from "better-auth"
import { Pool } from "pg"export const auth = betterAuth({
database: new Pool({ connectionString: process.env.DATABASE_URL }),
emailAndPassword: { enabled: true },
socialProviders: {
github: { clientId: process.env.GITHUB_ID!, clientSecret: process.env.GITHUB_SECRET! },
google: { clientId: process.env.GOOGLE_ID!, clientSecret: process.env.GOOGLE_SECRET! },
},
})// In a component
import { createAuthClient } from "better-auth/react"const authClient = createAuthClient()export function UserMenu() {
const { data: session } = authClient.useSession()
if (!session) return <a href="/login">Sign in</a>
return <p>Hello, {session.user.name}</p>
}
Auth.js v5 — Migration Bridge & OAuth Quick-Start
If you’re migrating from NextAuth v4 or need 80+ OAuth providers configured out of the box in minutes, Auth.js v5 (the stable rewrite) is still a solid pick. It now supports the App Router, React Server Components, and Edge runtime natively.
npm install next-auth@beta// auth.ts
import NextAuth from "next-auth"
import GitHub from "next-auth/providers/github"export const { handlers, auth, signIn, signOut } = NextAuth({
providers: [GitHub],
})// app/api/auth/[...nextauth]/route.ts
import { handlers } from "@/auth"
export const { GET, POST } = handlers
Clerk — Fastest Path to Production Auth
When time to market is the priority, Clerk delivers. Pre-built UI components for sign-in, sign-up, and user management, with zero backend setup. The free tier covers up to 50,000 monthly active users.
npm install @clerk/nextjs// app/layout.tsx
import { ClerkProvider, SignInButton, UserButton } from "@clerk/nextjs"export default function RootLayout({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
return (
<ClerkProvider>
<html lang="en">
<body>
<header>
<SignInButton />
<UserButton />
</header>
{children}
</body>
</html>
</ClerkProvider>
)
}
5. Data Fetching & APIs
tRPC v11 — End-to-End Type Safety
tRPC lets you call your server functions from the client as if they were local functions — with full TypeScript type inference, no code generation, and no REST or GraphQL overhead. v11 adds native React Server Component support.
npm install @trpc/server @trpc/client @trpc/react-query @tanstack/react-query// server/routers/user.ts
import { z } from "zod"
import { publicProcedure, router } from "../trpc"export const userRouter = router({
getById: publicProcedure
.input(z.object({ id: z.string() }))
.query(async ({ input }) => {
return await db.user.findUnique({ where: { id: input.id } })
}),
})// In a client component — fully type-safe
const { data } = trpc.user.getById.useQuery({ id: "user_123" })
// data is automatically typed — no manual typing needed
SWR — Lightweight Data Fetching by Vercel
For simpler apps where TanStack Query feels like overkill, SWR from the Next.js team is a lean, elegant alternative. The stale-while-revalidate pattern keeps UI snappy.
npm install swr"use client"
import useSWR from "swr"const fetcher = (url: string) => fetch(url).then(res => res.json())export function Dashboard() {
const { data, error, isLoading } = useSWR("/api/dashboard", fetcher, {
refreshInterval: 30000, // auto-refresh every 30s
}) if (isLoading) return <p>Loading...</p>
if (error) return <p>Failed to load.</p> return <h2>Welcome, {data.user.name}</h2>
}
6. ORM & Database
Prisma — The Established Standard
Prisma’s combination of a declarative schema, auto-generated type-safe client, and migration tooling makes it the most widely used ORM in the Next.js ecosystem. The Prisma Studio GUI for inspecting data is a developer experience win.
npm install prisma @prisma/client
npx prisma init// prisma/schema.prisma
model User {
id String @id @default(cuid())
email String @unique
name String?
posts Post[]
createdAt DateTime @default(now())
}model Post {
id String @id @default(cuid())
title String
content String?
author User @relation(fields: [authorId], references: [id])
authorId String
}// In a Server Component or API Route
import { PrismaClient } from "@prisma/client"const prisma = new PrismaClient()const users = await prisma.user.findMany({
include: { posts: true },
})
Drizzle ORM — The Fast-Rising Challenger
Drizzle is the fastest growing ORM in the ecosystem in 2026. It’s edge-compatible, has zero dependencies, and uses a SQL-like syntax that feels natural to developers who already know SQL. The first choice for Cloudflare Workers, Vercel Edge, and serverless functions.
npm install drizzle-orm drizzle-kit
npm install @libsql/client # for Turso / libSQL// db/schema.ts
import { text, integer, sqliteTable } from "drizzle-orm/sqlite-core"export const users = sqliteTable("users", {
id: text("id").primaryKey(),
email: text("email").notNull().unique(),
name: text("name"),
createdAt: integer("created_at", { mode: "timestamp" }).notNull(),
})// Querying
import { db } from "@/db"
import { users } from "@/db/schema"
import { eq } from "drizzle-orm"const user = await db.select().from(users).where(eq(users.email, "user@example.com"))
7. Testing
Vitest — The New Jest
Vitest is the unit and integration test runner
